        ACTUAL Chart Review 02/08/24

        [insert a joke that sets up the script for this review here]

        Isn't the summer grand? The endless heat-filled weekdays, the lack of school to put you off your M&Ms, and the feeling that you're never one holiday away from a major sporting event. Yes, the Olympics have been blaring from my TV (who needs a Discovery+ account when you have an Amazon Fire stick?) and I've been loving every minute of it. Well, apart from the same-old countries doing well, the whole world going mental anytime Israel do anything, and a situation where you can't go 5 minutes on Twitter without someone with a single-digit IQ raving on about The Last Supper getting massacred. Listen, geezers. No one asked you to sit through an opening ceremony with Lady Gaga, Zinedine Zidane and the Minions in it. The last thing you should be complaining about is an overgrown Smurf with his "reliable" out.

        But I'm here to take a break from rooting for the likes of Hong Kong and Guatemala to state that Radio 1 wasting 80 hours of my life with annoying dance cloggers like NewEra and Majestic is not ideal. And also, the Top 40, after I sacked it off yesterday. It doesn't take a genius to determine who ended up on the porcelain throne this week, Sabrina Carpenter continuing to prove that nobody is allowed to whisk her away to the Tower of London for crimes against British music. So it's yet another week for Please Please Please, meanwhile Eminem is also untouchable on the albums as well, his "I'm Dead, Honest" effort snatching a 3rd week at the top in the face of every female superstar you care to name. But there's more to the charts than this ya doofus.

        Thus, speculation has carried over to who will end up victorious at the end of all this tomfoolery in the next few weeks. You could be forgiven for betting all your life savings on BIRDS OF A FEATHER by Billie Eilish, considering it's finally usurped Sabrina at the Spotify top spot, but nope. She slips to 3 today, to accompdate the kind of song that will be sang by our descendants WAY past our funeral dates, the kind of hit that will aggravate certain people on this forum (you know who you are). And most importantly, it's probably not even peaked yet. So salutations to Chappell Roan for receiving another dollop of praise from my HQ, as Good Luck, Babe is now sitting pretty at No.2. Just a shame that, knowing my luck, she probably won't even reach the promised land in the end.

        Given how static the Top 10 has ended up by this point, you would think I'd give the latest newcomer to the best-sellers a chance to show us what it takes. Except when that track is Kisses by BL3SS, CamrinWatsin, bbyclose, and probably about 20 uncredited writers that we'll never hear from again because the TikTok generation are very picky when it comes to success. For every Mimi Webb or PinkPantheress, there's Kenya Grace. 21KGoldn. Ckay. Belters Only. GAYLE. I could go on all day. So take your pity points guys, 'cause I desperately hope to never hear from you lot again. The fact it's climbed to 7 is hardly my cup of tea, and I just know it's headed for the Top 3. In a dull world, anyway. Which I live in. And I hate it.

        So yeah, the future of music is in some horrible hands, but maybe Charli XCX can come and save us? What with 360 and Apple knocking on the glass ceiling, anything is possible. Jimin only slips to 11, certainly better than the 29 he was positioned in on Monday, but you can blame the army of fangirls and their multiple accounts for that stability. Oh, and JADE falls to 13. Which is fine, I guess. Ignore the fact her Spofity hopes have gone to seed, and you have probably the most successful solo career from the Little Mix girls. Potentially. Don't get your hopes up.

        Considering I couldn't care less about uploading this yesterday, I'll fly through the 3 new hits as if my life doesn't depend on it. Post Malone's 3rd effort in his country extravaganza lands at 26, doing better than his last collab which is all well and good, but this one has Luke Combs on it so maybe I should stop giving him false praise. Central Cee is back. AGAIN. And I genuinely couldn't tell you what gen z luv sounded like for the purposes of this review. And I've just listened to it. Maybe there's a good reason he's limped to 34. And at No.36, Calvin Harris takes this week's award for "Bottlejob Of The Day" by a massive landslide. Maybe it's because he keeps collaborating with Ellie Goulding, or maybe it's due to the slight issue that it's so workalike it could give Paul Weller a run for his money, but Free is just, SO BORING, that I'm not surprised it's flopped.

        It's gonna rocket up the charts now I've said that, isn't it. 😰

        But don't fret, folks. Because at No.30 is the latest in a long, long line of old songs suddenly getting a second wind this year and becoming hit-worthy all over again. You know how Stray Kidz roped Ryan Reynolds & Hugh Jackman for the video to their hit from last week? (down to 68 today, which is better than I thought.) Well, yeah, there's a good reason for that. Deadpool & Wolverine has been inescapable the last few weeks, and no, it's not because one of them owns a football club that's marginally better than Mansfield Town. Inevitably, the soundtrack is gonna have a few shocks and gasps, and who better to lead us to Nostalgia Land than *NSYNC. Remember those lot. They were the (somewhat boring, thinking about it) boyband that Justin Timberlake used to be in before he starting upsetting Britney Spears supporters and making songs that went on forever and ever (Mirrors, I'm looking at you). Bye Bye Bye originally reached No.3 in the heady days of 2000, so to see it suddenly rocket up the streaming charts and land at 30 today is nothing short of miraculous. It's like Florence + the Machine all over again.

        Outside the 40 and we have newbies from Sonny Fodera, Gigi Perez, Charli XCX, mgk, Aitch and D-Block Europe, Pharrell Williams, Gordo, and Tom Odell ruining the legacy of Black Friday for anyone and everyone. So onto next week I guess, and one of the above has duetted with Billie Eilish on a remix of one of their songs. Take a wild guess. And no, that pun wasn't intended. Honest. They'll be competing against Mimi Webb, Mura Masa, FLO, Sub Focus, Polo G and Khalid for chart supremacy, meanwhile over on the album chart, Jack White's surprise thingy he put out for no reason has to square up and brace itself. Because Kanye West is back with the 2nd of his VULTURES schtick, and I don't wanna be here for the fallout again. Except I will be. Too-da-loo.

        Just so you know, the reason for so many Jimin entries on iTunes is because the label botched the physicals (2 versions disallowed because of photocards) so they rush released two digital albums and a remix EP that all had the same 5 remixes and 1 instrumental of the track. So that is one original version, 5 remixes and 1 instrumental. They got listed separately and made a mess in the chart, but if there had been any double purchase they have been filtered out as per the chart rules. Seems like a lot of people are spreading rumours that there were tons and tons of remixes, but it certainly didn't have any more than most top ten hits have (you can see for yourself in any retailer). Jimin is currently in the South Korean military doing his mandatory service and can't do any promotion whatsoever, compared to other artists in the top ten, so to have scored such a high entry with no radio and no autoplay push is a sign of a crossover hit just like his song last year called Like Crazy. Why not give it listen and see what you think.
